gy of the 'Judeo-Christian' Signifier: A Tale of Europe's Identity Crisis -- tNotes on Contributors0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe term 'Judeo-Christian' in reference to a tradition, heritage, ethic, civilization, faith etc. has been used in a wide variety of contexts with widely diverging meanings. Contrary to popular belief, the term was not coined in the United States in the middle of the 20th century but in 1831 in Germany by Ferdinand Christian Baur. By acknowledging and returning to this European perspective and context, the volume engages the historical, theological, philosophical and political dimensions of the term's development. Scholars of European intellectual history will find this volume timely and relevant.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aChristianity and other religionsxJudaism. 0aJudaismxRelationsxChristianity. 0aTheology, DoctrinalzEurope. 4aEuropäische Geschichte. 4aJüdisch-christliche Beziehungen. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aEurope.  aF.C. Baur.  aJudeo-Christian Relations.1 aKluveld, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTopolski, Anya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmidt, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNathan, Emmanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, F. Stanley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalmer, Gesine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenyamini, Itzhak, econtributor.4ctb4https